<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level DELETE ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_manager` UNCONDITIONAL delete access
    on records of the `x_casemgmt_case_task` custom table inside the scoped
    application `x_casemgmt`. This is the DELETE companion to the case_manager
    create/read/write ACLs on the case_task table (whose granting ACLs are
    materialized by the sibling files
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_manager.xml,
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_manager.xml, and
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_manager.xml). Together those four files
    realize the AAP Section 0.5.6 manager row mirrored at the case_task table
    level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/
    x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml" ("Mirror ACL pattern at task level"):
    "x_casemgmt_case_manager : Create=Yes, Read=All, Write=All, Delete=Yes."

    Of the four CRUD operations, DELETE is the most-restricted on the case_task
    table: only the case_manager role gets it. There is intentionally NO
    sibling x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_agent.xml file and NO sibling
    x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_viewer.xml file - those two roles are denied
    delete by the ABSENCE of a granting ACL (ServiceNow record-level ACLs are
    deny-by-default; a role with no granting ACL for an operation cannot
    perform that operation). The deny is therefore enforced structurally - no
    scripted "deny" rule is required, and no inverse condition is encoded.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_manager row, mirrored at the
        case_task table level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml"
        ("Mirror ACL pattern at task level"):
            | Role                    | Create | Read | Write | Delete |
            | x_casemgmt_case_manager  |  Yes   | All  |  All  |  Yes   |
        This file authors the single "Delete = Yes" cell of the manager row
        for the case_task table. The "Yes" Create cell is authored by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_manager.xml; the "All" Read cell
        by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_manager.xml; the "All" Write cell
        by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_manager.xml. Each row of the ACL
        matrix maps to exactly one or zero ACL XML files - this per-cell
        granularity is what lets the Update Set add or remove role privileges
        independently without entangling roles or operations.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - all-roles delete coverage on case_task:
            - case_manager: Delete=Yes -> THIS FILE
            - case_agent:   Delete=No  -> deliberate absence of any
                                          x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_agent.xml
            - case_viewer:  Delete=No  -> deliberate absence of any
                                          x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_viewer.xml
        Together these three facts implement the user prompt's contract that
        only managers - who own records-management discipline for the entire
        case lifecycle including its child task records - may destroy task
        records. Agents (who merely process and close assigned tasks per the
        AAP Section 0.5.5 In Progress -> Resolved transition rule "All linked
        x_casemgmt_case_task records have status = Closed") and viewers (audit/
        compliance/supervisor tier with read-only access) cannot delete. This
        protects the historical audit trail that "All tasks must be closed
        before resolving this case." (verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4 wording)
        depends on - allowing agents to delete tasks would let an agent
        circumvent the resolved-transition gate by simply removing the
        offending open task instead of closing it.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
            "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write; case_agent
             cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has full access."
        The clause "case_manager has full access" requires that the manager
        role be able to perform every CRUD operation on the case_task table,
        of which delete is the fourth and most-elevated. This ACL satisfies
        that clause for the delete operation on the task domain; the parallel
        clauses about case_viewer (no write) and case_agent (no unassigned
        access) are unaffected by this ACL and are enforced by separate
        sibling ACL files (case_viewer never appears in any case_task
        write/create/delete ACL; case_agent delete on case_task is enforced
        by the deliberate absence noted above).
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based access
        control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and field-level
        ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL expressions,
        replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig map." This ACL
        is the table-level DELETE binding for the highest-tier scoped role on
        the task domain and is one of the declarative facts the platform's
        sys_security_acl evaluator consumes when authorizing a row deletion
        at runtime against the case_task table.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "ApplicationRolesConfig + RolesPrivilegesService +
        URL-based privilege metadata -> scoped roles + ACLs." In ArkCase the
        equivalent of THIS file would have been a single entry in the
        rolesToPrivileges map binding the manager-equivalent role to a
        privilege identifier such as `acm-task-delete` or `acm-task-remove`,
        evaluated at HTTP request time by AcmPluginUrlPrivilege against the
        DELETE verb on the task plugin's REST endpoint. The ServiceNow target
        replaces both the map binding and the URL-privilege evaluator with
        this single declarative ACL record.
      - Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map): the In Progress ->
        Resolved transition is gated by the rule "All linked
        x_casemgmt_case_task records have status = Closed" with the verbatim
        blocking-error message "All tasks must be closed before resolving
        this case." This transition contract assumes task rows persist for
        the duration of the case lifecycle so the validate_resolved_transition
        subflow (../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml) can
        enumerate them via GlideRecord and check their status. Allowing the
        agent role to delete tasks would create a trivial bypass of this
        contract - an agent unable to close an assigned task could simply
        delete it and the resolved-transition gate would falsely succeed.
        Restricting delete to manager-only (with full-access semantics)
        means the manager - who has organizational authority and oversight -
        is the only actor who can purge a task, and they do so deliberately
        rather than as an evasive workaround.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section 0.3.2;
    no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/services/
        users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration map
        (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by the property
        `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that model, a "manager-equivalent"
        role (e.g., ROLE_TASK_MANAGER) would have been associated with a
        delete privilege identifier such as `acm-task-delete`. The ServiceNow
        target replaces this map-based privilege association with declarative,
        scoped record-level ACLs - this XML record is the direct equivalent
        of one cell in the map: the (case_manager, DELETE) pairing on the
        case_task domain.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        `removeRolesPrivileges(...)`). All of this Java service surface is
        replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted privilege resolver is needed.
        Notably, ArkCase's `userDao.deleteAcmRole(roleName)` call removed an
        entire role definition - that operation has no analog in this file
        because role definitions in ServiceNow are themselves managed by the
        ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_*.xml records, not by ACLs. THIS
        ACL governs the deletion of CASE_TASK RECORDS, not the deletion of
        the role itself, and not the deletion of CASE records (that is
        governed separately by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_delete_manager.xml).

    Why advanced=false (no scripted condition for delete):
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6, the case_manager role's privileges are
      unconditional ("All", "Full access") - there is no "Assigned only" or
      other row-level filter. Therefore:
        - <advanced>false</advanced>      - no scripted condition
        - <condition/>                    - empty encoded query (no row filter)
        - <script/>                       - empty server-side script
      With no condition and no script, the ACL evaluates to "permit" for any
      caller who carries the x_casemgmt_case_manager role. This is the correct
      semantic for the AAP's "manager has full delete" requirement. Setting
      advanced=true with an empty script would be functionally equivalent
      but stylistically incorrect - the ServiceNow convention is to reserve
      advanced=true for ACLs that actually carry a scripted body (e.g., the
      ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml and
      ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml siblings, which
      DO carry "Assigned only" filter scripts).

    Why DELETE is granted to manager only (design rationale):
      - Records-management discipline: case_task records are the durable
        audit trail of every action taken on a case. Deletion is irreversible
        and removes audit trail. Agents perform tasks; viewers observe
        tasks; only managers - who own the lifecycle from intake to closure
        and bear records-management responsibility - have authority to
        remove task records.
      - State-machine integrity: the AAP Section 0.5.5 transition rule
        "All linked x_casemgmt_case_task records have status = Closed"
        determines whether a case may move from In Progress to Resolved.
        The `validate_resolved_transition` subflow
        (../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml) implements
        this rule by querying child task rows and counting non-Closed
        statuses. If the agent role could delete tasks, an agent unable to
        legitimately close an assigned task could simply delete it -
        bypassing the gate and corrupting the case lifecycle contract.
        Restricting delete to managers eliminates this bypass.
      - Reporting integrity: the Agent Workspace dashboard
        (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_agent_workspace.xml) computes
        "My overdue tasks" from the entire case_task table for the current
        user. Allowing agents to delete would let any agent silently
        clear their overdue-task count by deleting rows instead of closing
        them, which would defeat the dashboard's KPI integrity for managers
        observing agent productivity.
      - Portal anonymity contract: the external Experience Portal
        (../portal/sp_portal_x_casemgmt_case_portal.xml) accepts anonymous
        case submissions through ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml
        but DOES NOT expose any task-level capability. Anonymous callers
        and unauthenticated portal users have NO scoped role at all and
        therefore - by the same deny-by-default principle - have NO delete
        capability via this ACL. The portal contract is preserved
        automatically, and tasks remain an internal-only concern.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package source =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_casemgmt_case_task (not the OOB
        `task` or `incident_task` table or any other global table), and
        <roles> references the scoped role x_casemgmt_case_manager. There
        are zero global writes from this file.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by
        name / source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The
        <sys_id> below is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_case_task.delete.case_manager", a stable
        canonical identifier for this exact ACL) and is not a
        cross-reference to any other record. Computing the sys_id
        deterministically guarantees the ACL is re-applyable / idempotent
        across fresh PDIs and round-trip Update Set previews per AAP
        Section 0.7.3 Gate 7 ("Update Set loads without errors on a fresh
        PDI instance").
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case_task`
        with NO dot. ServiceNow's delete operation has no concept of
        "delete this specific column" - field-level ACLs apply only to
        read/write/none. The <type>record</type> field below confirms
        this is a row-level (table-level) ACL, not a UI/REST/SOAP-flavored
        ACL.
      - Operation = delete: corresponds exactly to the "Delete = Yes" cell
        in the AAP matrix for the case_manager role mirrored to the
        case_task table.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required so
        platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or remove
        scoped seed task data (per AAP Section 0.7.4 the
        ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js script can re-seed a fresh PDI; if
        a prior partial run left stale demo task rows, the admin user -
        who does NOT need the scoped case_manager role - must still be
        able to clean up). It does NOT widen case_manager privileges -
        non-admin managers see exactly what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = false: see "Why advanced=false" rationale above. The
        platform skips the empty <script/> body entirely.
      - condition (empty): the <condition/> encoded-query field is empty;
        no row-level filter applies to manager deletes (manager has "full"
        access, not "Assigned only").
      - script (empty): the <script/> field is empty; the platform skips
        it because advanced=false.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml (resolves
          <name>x_casemgmt_case_task</name> by table name lookup at apply
          time)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles> by role name lookup at
          apply time)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml
          (the demo manager's delete access during round-trip
          verification depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - any cleanup or re-seed activity in ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
          that may delete prior demo task rows; while seed_demo_data.js
          itself runs as admin and bypasses this ACL via admin_overrides,
          post-seed smoke tests against the demo dataset depend on this
          ACL being applied so a logged-in demo manager can validate
          end-to-end task-delete capability.
      The deny-by-default sibling pairs that this file works with:
        - x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_agent.xml  (DOES NOT EXIST - by design)
        - x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_viewer.xml (DOES NOT EXIST - by design)
      Adding either of those files would VIOLATE the AAP Section 0.5.6
      matrix and MUST NOT be done by any future agent.

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used verbatim per AAP convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"). ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
    scope id is concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped application. The deterministic sys_id below is computed against the
    `casemgmt` literal and remains stable across re-imports onto fresh PDIs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>false</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Allows users with the x_casemgmt_case_manager role to delete case_task records. Only role with delete privilege per AAP Section 0.5.6.</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case_task</name>
        <operation>delete</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles>
        <script/>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>6c1bd40bcab435a7951bfeb732cd90e0</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_case_task</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_manager</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
